PHOTO OF THE DAY - The barbell front squat is a very effective squat variation, and when compared to the back squat, is just plain hard work! In addition, the carryover to sport and life cannot be ignored.
The hamstring and gluteal muscles are also utilized during this exercise but because the center of gravity of the weight is actually shifted forward on the body it tends to place more stress on the quadriceps, thereby developing them even more.

The shin angle in the front squat will have more forward inclination when compared to the back squat, where it has more of a vertical shin. This allows more knee flexion to occur, stressing the quads even more. This in no means puts undue stress upon the knee joint per se, as long as the lifter goes below parallel with each repetition. Not going below parallel will tend to stress out the knee joint et al and not activate the gluteus maximus completely.

There are three different rack styles of the front squat taught at Iron Fitness Singapore. The first style we teach is the bodybuilding rack, which utilizes a crossed arm position. The second style is the traditional weightlifting rack, which is usually the standard rack that you will see in most gyms and facilities around the world, and especially in weightlifting competitions. The third rack style that we teach is what I term the powerlifting rack, which is a hybrid of the weightlifting rack, utilizing lifting straps to help hold the bar.

RANT: Damn you SMRT for wasting 2.5hours of my life. 2 major lines down simultaneously and no damage control AT ALL? I was stuck at Buona Vista for 50min and have seen absolutely ZERO shuttle bus service and regular buses were jammed full with people dashing onto the road trying to catch the bus. There was NO ground staff advising people and staff in the station had no idea that there was no shuttle service at all. Seeing that Buona is an interchange and no shuttle service was provided, what more other less crowded stations? Called every single taxi provider and none had available taxis. Taxi queues literally went up to a hundred people and every taxi was either hired or on call so the queue was practically not moving at all. After queuing in the taxi line at Buona for so long, a staff informed us that MRT service has resumed, only to find out at Jurong East that service at the N-S line has yet to resume. Hell no am I going to rejoin a taxi line that has more than a hundred people and the bus interchange at Jurong was brimming with people. Decided to take another station down to Chinese Garden where it was less crowded and begged to borrow phones from strangers to call a taxi cos mine ran out of batt. Finally managed to grab a taxi after 30minutes only because a vacant one happened to stop in front of me and not through cab calling services which was still inaccessible after 2hours. No MRT, no taxi, no bus, no shuttle bus. FML, although finally managing to grab that taxi at the end felt like one of the best moments in my life. Swear i thanked the taxi uncle at least 10times.

In view of the train breakdown yesterday evening, I took an earlier train to work today just to be on the safe side. It was in fact less crowded than usual (I usually can't even see my feet!!) and travelled at a normal speed, so it was definitely much faster than the forewarned reduced speed. I got to my workplace much earlier than usual so I had more time for a leisurely breakfast. 
Instead of ranting about how the train broke down yesterday and getting all angsty about it, I choose to view things in a positive light that the problem seemed largely resolved this morning for the commuters. I think over-efficiency in this country has led to many impatient people, myself included. I was caught in a traffic jam while in Bangkok recently and we took 2.5 hours to travel 12km! You bet I was feeling all angsty inside the taxi. 
We have a lot to be thankful for, being in this beautiful country, but sometimes whenever something goes wrong, we just focus on what's wrong and make a big fuss out of it. Let's spread a little positivity and love our country more, for all the good it has, rather than the little inconveniences we occasionally experience. #justsaying
